## What happened

In **.NET 11**, **DSA was removed from macOS**. `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS — it continues to work on Windows and Linux.

DSA is a legacy algorithm, and Apple's security libraries no longer support it, so .NET 11 dropped macOS support for it entirely.

## How to fix

Since you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), you have two options:

**Option 1 — Use ECDSA or RSA going forward** (recommended if you control the signing side):
```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
var valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

**Option 2 — Platform-guard the DSA path** (if you must verify existing DSA signatures):
```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
        "DSA signature verification is not supported on macOS with .NET 11+.");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```
Run DSA verification only on your Windows/Linux builds and migrate to **ECDSA** or **RSA** for new signatures across all platforms.
